# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: christian-vegetarianism
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] A&E was formed from the merger of the Alpha Repertory Television Service and the Entertainment Channel, a premium cable channel, in 1984 with their respective owners keeping stakes in the new company.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] Thus A&E's shareholders were Hearst and ABC (from ARTS) and Radio City Music Hall (Rockefeller Group) and RCA, then the parent of NBC (from Entertainment Channel).
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] The company launched A&E, at the time known as the Arts & Entertainment Network, on February 1, 1984, as a block on Nickelodeon to fill in the time slot that ARTS held, as ARTS was a block on Nick.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] In 1985, the partners spun off A&E into its own 24 hour channel, and Nickelodeon later created Nick at Nite to fill in the time slot that A&E formerly held.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] In 1990, after having aired episodes of its original 1960's version starting in 1987, A&E acquired rights to, and started producing new episodes of, the documentary series *Biography*— which became the channel's flagship program.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] The network also introduced its own companion magazine *A&E Monthly*.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] The company indicated that plans for a history channel were in the works in 1993; it purchased the Lou Reda Productions documentary library and long-term rights for the Hearst Entertainment documentaries archive.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] In June 1993, the Rockefeller Group's Radio City Music Hall sold its 12.5% stake in A&E to the other three partners (now including NBC in place of RCA after GE's purchase of the latter in 1986) with NBC owning 25% and the other two 37.5% each.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] Also that month, a new production unit was set up.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] The A&E channel expanded to Canada, and later Mexico from 1993 to 1994.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] *Biography* began airing 5 nights a week in 1994.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] Also in 1994, A&E, on its 10th anniversary, changed its name from Arts and Entertainment to A&E.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] A&E Networks launched the History Channel on January 1, 1995, with its UK counterpart following on November 1 in partnership with British Sky Broadcasting.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] A&E Networks considered History to be the driver in international expansion due to a lack of international rights to A&E international co-productions.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] As expected, the History Channel led A&E's overseas expansion in Brazil with TVA (April 1996), the Nordic and Baltic regions with Modern Times Group (1997), and in Canada (1997).
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] By 1997, the company had started its AETN International division.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] Formerly only direct sales, A&E Home Video initiated a six-month trial in which Barnes & Noble would sell the "Biography" line in stores, which became permanent in 1996.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] THC debuted in two other media in September 1996 with a radio program on ABC Radio Networks and Borders Books stocking THC videos.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] The 'Biography' franchise continued to expand with a website in July 1996, a children's version launched in fall 1996, an audiotape line in 1997, telefilm development, a Crown published short biography line and debuted its magazine which replaced A&E Monthly.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] During the 1998–1999 season, *Biography: American Justice* and *Biography Movies* debuted.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] History expanded in 1998 into tours of U.S. landmarks with Mayflower Tours having an affiliated website (historytravel.com), *History Channel Traveler*, and a planned quarterly magazine.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] While in October, History and MSG Network teamed up to produce several short-form sports history programs.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] A+E spun out its two digital cable channels in November 1998 with The Biography Channel and History Channel International from A&E and the History Channel.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] A&E was spending $10 million per year to convert to the digital format and for digital distribution.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] With the need to revive a battered channel, improve the brand and create strong content for the A&E channel, A&E executive started the A&E IndieFilms division in 2005.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] In August 2009, A&E Networks acquired Lifetime Entertainment Services (Lifetime, LMN, and Lifetime Real Women), which at the time was also jointly owned by Disney and Hearst, each with 50% ownership.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] Following the deal, Disney (owner of ABC) and Hearst each held approximately 42% of the combined company, while NBCUniversal retained approximately 16%.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] The deal included mechanisms by which NBCU could choose, or alternatively be forced to, exit the partnership over the subsequent 15 years.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] In May 2011, A&E Television Networks rebranded as "A+E Networks"; the new name was intended to signify its expansion towards other platforms besides television.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] In July 2012, NBCUniversal confirmed plans to divest its 15.8% stake in A+E Networks by way of a share repurchase, making Disney and Hearst 50-50 partners in the joint venture.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] In August 2012, A+E announced that Lionsgate Home Entertainment had acquired the home video distribution rights to its content, replacing New Video.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] With an early June 2013 promotion to A+E Networks CEO, Nancy Dubuc launched a new in-house production unit, A&E Studios, and hired veteran BBC executive Jana Bennett to serve as the president of Biography Channel and LMN.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] In December 2013, in response to stagnating viewership in comparison to its sister networks, it was announced that the Biography Channel would be re-launched as FYI, a lifestyle-oriented network, in 2014.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] The channel's new president, Jana Bennett, had previously overseen The Learning Channel's early-2000s transition into a mainstream lifestyle channel.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] In August 2014, A+E took a 10% stake in Vice Media for $250 million.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] The company then announced in April 2015 that H2 would be re-branded into a Vice channel with an indicated early 2016 launch.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] Director Spike Jonze, Vice's creative director, is overseeing the development of the new 24-hour channel.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] Disney also made a direct investment in Vice Media with two $200 million investments in November 2015 then a week later in December for about a direct 10% to assist in funding programming.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] In May 2016, the company signed an international distribution deal with Pulse Films, and its East Entertainment formats and entertainment company.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] A+E Networks took an equity stake at the March 2015 formation of an independent TV production company, Propagate Content, run and owned by CEO Howard T.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] Owens and chief creative officer David McKillop, former A&E channel general manager.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] The development team led by Daniel Suratt had the company also investing in Epic Magazine, Samba and Panna food app-based content company in December 2015.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] Sean Cohan was promoted from head of international division to president of international and digital media in December 2015 as Suratt, head of digital media & business development, was promoted to president of corporate development, strategy and investments.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] The company formed an in-house advertising agency, 45th & Dean, under executive vice president and general manager of FYI Network Paul Greenberg in May 2016.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] In February 2017, A+E's in-house ad agency, 45th and Dean, was planning on developing new shows for Snapchat's Discover platform.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] The Digital Media division launched its first direct to consumer streaming service, Lifetime Movie Club, in September 2015.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] Then in February 2016, the division launched another service, History Vault, followed by its Canadian version in November with Corus.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] Both have content at least a year off their respective channels.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] Club offers a rotating group of 40 films from the Lifetime library, while Vault has 400 documentaries at any one time.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] The new Vice channel, branded as Viceland, launched on September 19, 2016.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] The next day, A+E Networks UK launched Blaze, a new free-to-air channel carrying programming aimed towards adult males.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] In March 2017, the company invested in a Series A funding round for Beautycon.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] A&E led a Series A funding round for Atlas Obscura in mid-2017.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] AETN in November 2017 took a substantial minority stake in Dan Abrams's LawNewz Network live court content website, which then renamed its website to Law&Crime Network.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] In 2017, A+E Networks took a 25% equity stake in the National Women's Soccer League (NWSL), as part of a three-year media rights deal that saw Lifetime carry a package of weekly NWSL matches, and become a sleeve sponsor for all NWSL players.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] In February 2019, A+E ended the pact early and returned its 25% equity in the league, while continuing Lifetime's sleeve sponsorship.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] In the second quarter of 2017, A+E Networks relaunched the Biography franchise with a set of two-hour specials and a miniseries for three of its channels, A&E, History and Lifetime.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] The franchise's TV programming will be recurring multi-formatted and tie into important anniversaries, newly found information about notables and current news.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] The initial set has the commonality of being crime centered, with at least one future set would focus on notable women.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] A+E Networks held its first convention, Alien Con, October 28–30, 2016 in partnership with Cosmic Con as an extension of the History channel's *Ancient Aliens* TV series.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] A+E called back former CEO Abbe Raven to be interim CEO.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] Paul Buccieri was promoted from president of A&E Studios and A+E Networks Portfolio Group to A&E President in July 2018.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] Buccieri formed the A&E Originals unit for unscripted series.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] This was followed by three first look deals with Leah Remini, Elizabeth Vargas and Gretchen Carlson.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] Vargas would serve as anchor of its A&E Investigates banner.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] A+E Networks launched its first OTT channel, Lively Place, through Wurl on Samsung TV Plus in December 2019.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] A+E Networks sold several programs into the Latin American (DirecTV and Colombian broadcaster Plural TV) and US Hispanic (NBC Universo) markets in January 2019.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] This a part of attempt to offset declines in US basic cable business with sales to expanding markets like Latin America.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] A+E Networks agreed to a first-look development and production deal with Ozy Media in January 2020 for potential maker for A&E, History and Lifetime flagship cable channels.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] In February 2020, the company started its A&E Crime Central streaming service.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] The service has from the company's major channel libraries some 900 crime series and specials available.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] That year, it also licensed selected programs from the A&E and History libraries to NBCUniversal's new streaming service Peacock.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] In June 2021, A+E Networks acquired a 35% stake in Canadian studio Reel One Entertainment—one of the independent producers of Lifetime's television films—from Groupe TF1 subsidiary Newen.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] On April 3, 2024, A+E Networks partnered with Warner Bros.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] Discovery/Lionsgate Entertainment/Gray Media-owned Free TV Networks to become joint owners in a broadcast network called Defy, which was formerly owned by the E.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] Scripps Company's Scripps Networks division.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] It was later acquired in December 2025 and currently owned by Versant.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] On February 20, 2025, the company launched a new digital unit led by Ann McGowan.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] On July 8, 2025, Disney and Hearst are exploring the sale of A+E Global Media following Comcast plans to spin off of NBCUniversal’s cable networks into a new company Versant and WBD previously proposed the split of cable networks to Discovery Global before the buyout by Paramount Skydance.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] On November 16, 2025, Bloomberg reported that Starz Entertainment is interested in making a bid to buy A+E Global Media from Disney and Hearst Communications.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] A+E Networks formed the studio in June 2013 under president Bob DeBitetto with three projects in development, one for each flagship channels.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] At MIPCOM in October 2014, International executive vice president Sean Cohan and DeBitetto launched A+E Studios International as a distribution and financing unit to distribution A+E Studios productions.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] With the October 2016 retirement of DeBitetto, Paul Buccieri took over his post as president of A+E Studios and A+E Networks Portfolio Group from the post of president of A+E Network and History.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] Buccieri formed the A+E Originals unit for unscripted series placing Steve Ascher, Former History executive, in day-to-day charge as vice president in 2007.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] Soon thereafter in April 2018, A+E agreed to a third season for "Scientology and the Aftermath" documentary series and a first-look development deal with Leah Remini.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] Also in April 2018, A+E Originals signed Elizabeth Vargas to a first-look and production deal.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] Vargas would serve as anchor of its A+E Investigates, its banner for new non-fiction prime time journalism programming.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] In April 2018, A+E Originals signed a first-look deal with former Fox News anchor Gretchen Carlson to host three documentaries.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] Ascher was promoted to senior vice president, production and development of A+E Originals.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] In July 2019, Pop announced a series order from A+E Studios for *Best Intentions*.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] With the re-merger of Viacom-CBS in March 2020, Pop dropped the series and allowed A+E Studios to shop the show.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] More recently, the studio signed a deal with Silver Lining Entertainment Partners.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] A&E IndieFilms is the feature documentary film production division of A&E Studios, LLC with a staff of two.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] The subdivision was launched in 2005, in response to the success of theatrical documentaries such as *Fahrenheit 9/11* and *Super Size Me* and with the need to revive a battered channel, improve the brand and create strong content for the A&E channel.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] Molly Thompson was hired in 2005 for the division and executive produced all the division's films to 2009.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] Thompson was promoted to division vice president in January 2009, then senior vice president by April 2016.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] At this time, A&E IndieFilms was a division of A&E Studios.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] Thompson, senior vice president of feature films for A+E Networks at this time, left in January 2019 for Apple's streaming service in a similar position.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] History Films is a production company associated with the History channel and led by Molly Thompson as executive producer and head of documentary films for A+E Networks until January 2019.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] A+E Networks International is the international division of A+E Networks, which handles international operations outside the U.S., mostly through joint ventures.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] A&E is an associate member of: the Caribbean Cable & Telecommunications Association and the Caribbean Cable Cooperative.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] A+E Networks started AETN International by 1997 with A&E channel in Canada and Mexico and the History channel in the UK, Brazil, the Nordic and Baltic regions and in Canada.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] The History Channel UK was its first joint venture with British Sky Broadcasting.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] In 1997, A&E purchased a one-third stake in Mundo Olé.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] AETN All Asia Networks was formed in April 2007 through a joint venture between A&E Television Networks and Malaysia's pay TV provider Astro Overseas Limited.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] AETN and Network 18 Group in August 2010 formed a joint venture (49/51%), AETN-18 India, which would first launch the History and Bio channels in India.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] A&E International moved into France with a deal with Canal Plus Group for channel carriage in France on its CanalSat satellite platform in the second half of 2013 and A&E programs for Canal's D8 and D17 free-to-air channels.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] In July 2013, A+E Networks bought out Astro Overseas's stake in AETN All Asia Networks and renamed it to A+E Networks Asia.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] A&E Networks Italy was established in December 2013, launching the local version of Crime & Investigation, as well as buying out the Italian version of History from its local partner, Fox International Channels.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] A&E Networks UK launched the Blaze channel on 20 September 2016 as its first free-to-air channel.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] In December 2016, the company appointed Patrick Vien and Edward Sabin as executive managing directors and co-heads of international reporting to Sean Cohan, A+E Networks' president of international and digital media.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] Vien oversaw Europe, the Middle East and Africa operations and programming acquisitions, sales and strategy for all non-US channels.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] Operations in Latin America, Canada, Asia, Australia and New Zealand would be overseen by Sabin along with global operations team and A&E formation production.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] Sabin was promoted from managing director of the Americas and head of commercial operations, while Vien left a post at Pulse Film.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] On September 20, 2016, A&E Networks UK launched Blaze, a new free-to-air channel carrying programming aimed towards adult males.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] In May 2017, the company extended its distribution deal with Sky for the UK, Ireland, Italy, Germany, and Austria market (A+E Networks U.K., A+E Networks Germany, A+E Networks Italy) channels.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] A+E Networks Asia launched Its Korea country unit in October 2017 with two channels.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] The plan was approved on January 28, 2019, 9 days after the globally announced closure of the transaction with Hearst assuming full ownership of all entities.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] Vien was promoted to group managing director – International, A+E Networks in July 2019 with Sabin exiting the company.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] In October 2019, Twentieth Television executive Steve MacDonald was hired as president of its global content licensing and international division over Vien.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] In July 2019, a managing director, Asia which consolidates the Asia region again including Southeast Asia, Taiwan, Hong Kong and India.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] The international division began a push into production in the late 2010s.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] With Element 8, A&E produced *Miss Scarlet and the Duke*, which was sold in December 2019 to Masterpiece (US), Alibi channel(UK), CBC (Canada), Seven Network (Australia) and RTL (Germany).
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] A+E Networks International agreed in November 2019 to globally distribute its first Spanish-language series, Hernán, by Spain's Onza Entertainment and Dopamine, units of Grupo Salinas.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] On September 12, 2024, A+E Networks EMEA rebranded to Hearst Networks EMEA.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] A+E Networks Latin America is a joint venture between A+E Networks International and Ole Communications.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] In 1996, HBO Latin America Group and Venezuela's Olé Communications began a basic cable channel joint venture Mundo Olé in Mexico.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] The channel was launched in October 1996.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] With in a year, A&E was supplying 60% of the channel's shows.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] In 1998, Mundo began producing local Biography episodes.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] In 2000, the word Olé was dropped, causing Mundo Olé to become Mundo.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] The next year, Mundo was renamed to A&E Mundo but continued airing the Biography series.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] The channel was renamed once more as A&E in 2005.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] Back in 1992, History Latin America was launched as TVQuality.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] It continued to use that name until 2000, when it became The History Channel.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] From 2008, it is still History since then.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] In 2012, A&E Latin America opened an office in Brazil.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] The Biography Channel was launched in Latin America in 2007; however, when the US Bio. network became FYI in 2014, The Latin American network is now H2 since then.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] Lifetime Latin America was launched in July 2014 as a joint venture between A+E Networks Latin America and Sony Pictures Television with distribution by HBO Latin America Group.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] As of 2020, A+E Networks Latin America channels continue to be distributed across Latin America through Ole Distribution.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] The three original programs, "History Alive", "Our Century", and "Biography", were British hosted and tailored.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] The joint venture expanded with the launching of Military History channel in July 2008.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] Soon thereafter, The History Channel was rebranded to History.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] Crime and Investigation and Bio launched in HD on Sky UK and Sky Ireland on 5 November 2008.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] The History Channel UK joint venture was renamed to AETN UK on July 2, 2009.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] A+E Networks UK with Netflix and Sky Vision in April 2016 on *I Am a Killer* true crime 10-episode show for Crime + Investigation Network with a UK spring debut followed by Italy's and Poland's Crime + Investigation airing later in the year.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] Then the show would be available on Netflix.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] The plan was approved on January 28, 2019, 9 days after the globally announced closure of the transaction with Hearst assuming full ownership of AETN UK.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] AETN UK launched two subscription video on demand channels in May 2019 and June 2019, History Play and Crime+Investigation Play, respectively.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] In May 2020, History and H2 were renamed Sky History and Sky History 2 respectively, to match Sky's two new channels (Sky Documentaries and Sky Nature) which launched at the same time.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] A joint venture with NBCUniversal International from 2005 to 2017, the US parent company decided in June 2017 to take complete control of its German spin-off, based in Munich.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] A+E Networks Germany operates the two pay TV channels: History and A&E in Germany, Austria, Switzerland, Luxembourg, Liechtenstein and South Tyrol.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] The company also operated *The Biography Channel Germany* from 31 March 2007 until 22 September 2014 which was then replaced by *A+E Germany*.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] To gain regulatory approval of Disney's acquisition of most of 21st Century Fox's assets, it agreed to sell its 50% stake to Hearst.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] The plan was approved on January 28, 2019, 9 days after the globally announced closure of the transaction with Hearst assuming full ownership of The History Channel (Germany) GmbH &Co KG.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] A+E Networks had launched History Channel in Italy as joint-venture with Fox International Channels.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] A&E has established a local office in December 2013 and has launched Crime and Investigation on December 16.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] The joint-venture with Fox was planned for buy out in early 2014.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] While, A&E Italy has been producing locally with some of them being picked up international, the company began producing or commissioning films with international potential being with its 2018 releases.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] The first of this group was *Emanuela Orlandi/Vanished Special* picked up by Sky in Italy, Germany's ZDF and Belgian public television RTBF and produced by B&B Film.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] The plan was approved on January 28, 2019, 9 days after the globally announced closure of the transaction with Hearst assuming full ownership of A&E Television Networks Italy Srl.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] The History Channel Iberia is a joint venture of A+E Networks and AMC Networks International Southern Europe, formerly Multicanal then Chello Multicanal.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] A+E Networks has launched Canal de Historia in Spain and Portugal in 1996 in joint-venture with Multicanal.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] In 2005 was launched The Biography channel (later Bio), which was replaced by A&E on 2 October 2014., and later, on 18 April 2018 A&E was replaced by Blaze.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] Crime & Investigation Network was launched on 1 February 2011.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] The plan was approved on January 28, 2019, 9 days after the globally announced closure of the transaction with Hearst assuming full ownership of The History Channel, Iberia SL (Spain).
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] AETN All Asia Networks (AAAN) was formed in April 2007 through a joint venture between A&E Television Networks and Malaysia's pay TV provider Astro Overseas Limited to serve in the Southeast Asian, Hong Kong and Taiwanese markets.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] History and Crime & Investigation Network were launched in Singapore, Malaysia, Hong Kong, and Brunei on June 15, 2007, with the History Channel only in Thailand.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] A December launch was expected for the Philippines.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] In 2008, AAAN planned to launch the Biography Channel.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] In 2009, AETN Asia Networks struck a US$800,000 co-production deal with the National Film Development Corporation of Malaysia to co-produce programs to be featured across its channels.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] It has recently hired SPE Networks as a regional ad sales representative across the South East Asian region.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] In the late first half of 2013, All Asia Networks launched Lifetime and H2.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] In July, A+E Networks bought out Astro Overseas's stake in AETN All Asia Networks and renamed it to A+E Networks Asia.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] Its Korea country unit was launched in October 2017 with two channels, History and Lifetime, under general manager Youngsun Soh.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] With Alan Hodges leaving as managing director of Asia-Pacific, the unit was split into Southeast Asia & Australia and North Asia (Korea, Japan and China) in May 2018.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] The managing director for Southeast Asia and Australia appointed was Leena Singarajah from Scripps Network.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] The managing director for North Asia appointed was Saugato Banerjee.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] Saugato Banerjee was named in July 2019 as managing director, Asia which consolidates the Asia region including Southeast Asia, Taiwan, Hong Kong and India under him.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] Formerly known as AETN-18 India, a joint venture between Network18 Group, A+E Networks India is the Indian branch of A+E Networks Asia that operates around South Asia.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] A+E Networks Home Entertainment is the home entertainment division of A+E Networks.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] It creates and distributes content from A+E Networks' channels included A&E, Biography & History branded products.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-e-television-networks] It also distributes content it has acquired the rights to including hit American television series, British comedies, cult TV and sports programming.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner obtained his M.D. from Yale Medical School in 1909 and received the Campbell Gold Medal for the highest rank on his examination and the Keese Prize for his thesis.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-fleshless-diet] In 1916, Buttner was described by the editor of the *Journal of the American Medical Association* as a "recognized representative in the literature of vegetarianism." He argued for vegetarianism from a scientific basis.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner practiced medicine in New Haven, Connecticut.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-fleshless-diet] He was a member of the New Haven County Medical Association.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner is best known for his vegetarian book *A Fleshless Diet*, published in 1910.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-fleshless-diet] It was widely reviewed in medical journals with a mixed response.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner argued that comparative anatomy and nutrition demonstrates that man is suited for a fleshless diet and that meat is dangerous and unnecessary.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-fleshless-diet] His recommended diet consisted of vegetables, eggs and milk.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner wrote that "It is not illogical for vegetarians to use milk and eggs, as these animal products are distinctly less toxic than meat and also less likely to be disease-laden.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-fleshless-diet] A review in the *American Physical Education Review*, praised the book for compiling useful dietetic research but commented that it failed to show scientific discretion in the selected material.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-fleshless-diet] A review in the *Journal of the American Medical Association* recommended the book as a reference work whether or not one accepts Buttner's conclusions.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-fleshless-diet] A review in *The Medical Standard*, noted that the book was a "piece of special pleading for the propaganda which it is designed to promote […] We may say this, however, for Dr.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Robert Morris (1703–1754) was an English writer on architecture.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] His published works include *Lectures on Architecture* (1734–36), *An Essay on Harmony* (1739), and *The Art of Architecture* (1742).
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also wrote poems, essays, and pamphlets, and worked as a surveyor.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] According to Adams, Morris encountered *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood* in 1745.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Expecting an argument against flesh-eating, he instead found a defence of meat consumption based on a post-Flood reading of Genesis.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris disagreed with that interpretation and wrote a reply, which was published in 1746 as *A Reasonable Plea for the Animal Creation*.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] The treatise is made up of a preface, a letter to General Foliot, nine letters addressed to a friend, and a concluding reply to *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood*.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams writes that the central part of the book consists of letters Morris had written in 1737 and 1738 and later incorporated into the printed work.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris argues that humans have no natural right to kill animals for food.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He appeals both to Genesis and to "the nature and reason of things", maintaining that the food originally given to humans was the produce of the earth.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He rejects attempts to justify meat-eating through scripture, custom, bodily necessity, or animal predation.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also argues that humans are not naturally fitted for carnivory, and describes butchery and cookery as artificial practices rather than natural ones.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Drawing on writers such as Pythagoras and Plutarch, he attributes feeling and a degree of rationality to animals and treats their destruction for food as a matter of cruelty and injustice.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In her introduction to the 2005 republication, Carol J.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams describes the treatise as a neglected contribution to 18th-century vegetarian and animal-ethical writing.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She argues that Morris' case against flesh-eating is centred less on health than on moral obligation, and that his appeal to the "light of Nature" gives the work a distinctive place among early vegetarian texts.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams also comments on the book's epistolary form, noting that its letters are addressed to a flesh-eating friend.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She treats that structure as part of the book's argument, since Morris repeatedly answers objections and defends vegetarianism against the assumptions of a meat-eating society.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She further notes Morris' rejection of claims of human superiority and his attribution of sentience and reason to animals.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] On Adams' reading, these features connect the treatise to later debates in animal ethics.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Before its republication in 2005, the treatise had appeared only occasionally in modern writing.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Whisker, John Simons, and Rod Preece each referred to it as an early contribution to vegetarian and animal-ethical thought.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Simons described Morris, together with John Hildrop, as a precursor to Humphry Primatt.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Preece quoted from the treatise and placed Morris among earlier writers who argued for vegetarianism on ethical grounds, including John Oswald, George Nicholson, Joseph Ritson, and John Frank Newton.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In 2005, the treatise was republished in *Organization & Environment* with an introductory article by Carol J.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-sacred-duty] The film opens with footage of a NASA rocket launch, an animation of the Solar System, and a quote from Deuteronomy 30:19 about choosing between life and death (illustrated with images of Earth as seen from space, contrasted with an exploding atom bomb).
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-sacred-duty] This is followed by a statement that humanity has not been caring for the planet properly according to Jewish teachings, which precedes a section about ancient Jewish texts and sacred words that provide "specific instructions on how to be custodians of the world in which we live".
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-sacred-duty] Throughout the film, quotes from the Torah are contrasted with the various environmental threats facing humanity today; the quotes are also illustrated with close-ups of Hebrew scrolls, Jews praying, and scenes of nature.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-sacred-duty] The Earth is again seen from space and the camera moves in to focus on Israel, which the narrator cites as a microcosm of current global problems related to air and water pollution, overpopulation, climate change, and health concerns.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-sacred-duty] The film moves on to look at global problems, with scenes shot all over the world.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-sacred-duty] The focus then shifts to the United States, where all the relevant issues are discussed in detail.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-sacred-duty] Reference is made to *Livestock's Long Shadow*, a 2006 report by the Food and Agriculture Organization which claimed that livestock agriculture produces more greenhouse gases than all of the world's vehicles combined.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-sacred-duty] Next comes a brief presentation, illustrated with simple animated charts, on how meat production is an inefficient way to produce food for a hungry world.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-sacred-duty] This moves into footage of animal abuse on feedlots and in factory farms, and the pollution produced by these facilities.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-sacred-duty] The film then focuses on the advantages of vegetarianism for reducing pollution and solving world hunger.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-sacred-duty] With a change of diet toward vegetarianism, the film asserts that many of these environmental and health problems can be solved.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-sacred-duty] After some fast-moving images of people and nature accompanied by music, the film ends with the same statement from Deuteronomy about "life and death" being narrated over a shot of a sunrise.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-sacred-duty] The idea for the film was inspired by the writings of Richard H.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-sacred-duty] Schwartz (*Judaism and Vegetarianism*, *Judaism and Global Survival*, etc.) who also served as associate producer.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-sacred-duty] Schwartz had seen the Christian Vegetarian Association's 2006 film, *Honoring God's Creation*, and felt that a similar film would be effective in the Jewish community.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-sacred-duty] At the time, he envisioned the film to be about 30 minutes long, though the final film ended up being 60 minutes long.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-sacred-duty] Production began in 2005 with a basic proposal and outline in the JVNA's newsletter, along with a statement that Lionel Friedberg was willing to make the film for "a very low fee, basically to cover his costs".
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-sacred-duty] The film was funded by the JVNA through private contributions.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-sacred-duty] Preliminary drafts of the script were circulated among members of the JVNA advisory committee and others for input, after which the script went through numerous revisions.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-sacred-duty] Meanwhile, Schwartz and Friedberg set about interviewing possible participants and filming footage of nature in both Israel and the United States.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-sacred-duty] The showing of slaughterhouse footage was controversial, with some members of a test audience in Staten Island seeing it as propaganda.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-sacred-duty] Friedberg recalled, "Richard and I were accused of making a propaganda film for the vegetarian movement.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-sacred-duty] We were accused of showing 'horrors that are impossible to watch'." However, he maintained that the graphic footage was necessary.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-sacred-duty] In October and November 2007, *A Sacred Duty* was released direct-to-video and on DVD, with public showings in both Israel and the United States.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-sacred-duty] Over 35,000 copies were distributed free of charge to synagogues, educational institutions, and individuals, complete with permission to show the film without having to pay the filmmakers any royalties.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-sacred-duty] In addition, permission was granted to the public to duplicate and distribute the film free of charge.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/a-sacred-duty] Numerous short excerpts from the film were edited and re-posted by various YouTube users, and the full version became available on YouTube in January 2008.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] The Australian Broadcasting Corporation (ABC) owns and operates a network of terrestrial radio stations that broadcast across Australia on AM and FM frequencies, DAB+, DVB-T, and the internet.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] This includes 11 national networks and 53 local stations operated through the ABC Local Radio division.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] The ABC also broadcasts to the Asia-Pacific region with Radio Australia.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] The ABC was founded in 1932 to take over the production duties of the Australian Broadcasting Company and operation of the Postmaster-General's Department's National Broadcasting Service.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] Upon its establishment, it operated 12 stations across Australia, and invested in six symphony orchestras.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] The ABC expanded over the following decades, opening and acquiring more stations, and establishing new national networks: Radio National, ABC NewsRadio, Triple J, and ABC Classic.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] Consolidation in the 1990s led to the divestment of the orchestras – which spun off into Symphony Australia – and the centralisation of operations into new headquarters in Sydney and Melbourne.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] Regular digital radio and internet radio broadcasts commenced in 2009 and 2012, respectively.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] The first public radio station in Australia opened in Sydney on 23 November 1923 under the call sign 2SB.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] Other stations in Melbourne, Brisbane, Adelaide, Perth and Hobart followed.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] A licensing scheme administered by the Postmaster-General's Department, was soon established allowing certain stations government funding, albeit with restrictions placed on their advertising content.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] In 1924 the licensing system was changed.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] The Postmaster-General's Department collected all licence fees and broadcasters were funded as either A-Class or B-Class stations.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] A-Class stations received government funding and were able to take limited advertising, while B-Class stations received no government funding but could carry more advertising.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] By 1925 many of the A-Class stations were in financial difficulty.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] A 1927 Royal Commission into wireless broadcasting recommended that radio licence fees be pooled to fund larger A-Class stations.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] The government established the National Broadcasting Service to take over the 12 A-Class licences as they came up for renewal from 1928.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] The original legislation permitted advertising, but this was removed from the Act before it came into effect.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] At the same time, the government created the Australian Broadcasting Company to supply programs to the new national broadcaster.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] Initially the Postmaster-General's Department, which operated postal and telephone services, was responsible for operating the National Broadcasting Service, although this arrangement did not have universal political support.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] As a result, the Australian Broadcasting Commission was established on 1 July 1932 to take over the Australian Broadcasting Company and run the National Broadcasting Service.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] The ABC was to be based on the BBC model, funded primarily through listener license fees, with some direct government grants.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] These formed the basis for the present-day ABC Local Radio and Radio National networks.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] Conductor Sir Bernard Heinze was appointed to the position of part-time musical adviser to the ABC in 1934.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] In 1937, the network was further expanded with the purchase of Brisbane's 4BC.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] Two years later, the commission began publishing the *ABC Weekly* - a radio magazine promoting the ABC's local radio, and later television, programs.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] Among the other early programs were the stations' famous 'synthetic' cricket broadcasts - when tests were played in England, commentators in the ABC's Sydney studios used cables from London and sound effects to recreate the match in play.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] In addition, all 38 of William Shakespeare's plays were performed live between 1936 and 1938.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] Local drama was produced, with a competition for plays and sketches from Australian authors held in 1934.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] Talks from prominent figures of the time such as King George V, Pope Pius XI, British Prime Minister Ramsay MacDonald, Adolf Hitler and H.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] During the broadcaster's first decades, programs generally consisted of music, news and current affairs, sport, drama, children's educational supplements and school broadcasts.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] The ABC hired its first journalist in 1934, and the service continued to be expanded, with the appointment of a federal news editor in 1936, and in 1939 a Canberra correspondent to cover national politics.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] Because recording technology was still relatively primitive, all ABC programs (including music) were broadcast live until 1935, when the first disc-based recorder was installed at the commission's Sydney studios.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] For this purpose, the ABC established broadcasting orchestras in each state, and in some centres employed choruses and dance bands.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] Throughout the early-to-mid 1930s, the stations were reformed into a cohesive broadcasting organisation through regular program relays, coordinated by a centralised bureaucracy.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] The Australian broadcast radio spectrum at the time was made up of the ABC and the commercial sector.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] Though regular program relays were in place between the ABC's stations in Sydney, Melbourne, Brisbane, Adelaide and Perth; it was not until 1936 that Hobart was connected with the mainland, through a cable under the Bass Strait.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] News bulletins, however, continued to be read in each state from local newspapers (by agreement with the Newspaper Proprietors Association).
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] During World War II, the ABC continued to recruit staff, including a greater proportion of women to replace men who had joined the armed forces.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] The organisation established reporting and recording facilities in a number of overseas locations, including the Middle East, Greece and around the Asia-Pacific region.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] An early challenge to its independence came in June, 1940 when wartime censorship was imposed, meaning that the Department of Information (headed by Keith Murdoch) took control of the ABC's 7 p.m. nightly national news bulletin.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] This lasted until September, when control of the news was returned to the ABC after listeners expressed a preference for independent news presented by the commission.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] On 7 January 1941, the ABC revived the Children's Session as a national program, including the *Argonauts Club*, which was first broadcast in 1933–34 in Melbourne.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] The *Argonauts Club* proved hugely popular with young Australians - by 1950 there were over 50,000 members, with 10,000 new members joining each year through the 1950s.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] The Club encouraged children's contributions of writing, music, poetry and art, and became one of the ABC's most popular programs, running six days a week for 28 years.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] In the late 1940s, "serious" programming such as news, current affairs, and features — early forms of what became known as documentaries — were moved to the commission's national network, with lighter entertainment programming left for the metropolitan stations.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] A Light Entertainment department was formed, to produce programs such as *ABC Hit Parade*, *The Wilfrid Thomas Show*, Bob Dyer's *Dude Ranch* and *The Village Glee*.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] In December 1945, rural and regional affairs program *The Country Hour* premiered.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] The ABC's coverage of rural affairs was significantly enhanced by the deployment of journalists and 'extension officers' to major country areas.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] The increasing availability of landlines and teleprinters throughout the late 1940s allowed the organisation to gather and broadcast news and other program material with much greater efficiency than in the previous two decades.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] By this time, as many as 13 national news bulletins were broadcast daily.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] Legislation passed in 1946 requiring the ABC to broadcast Parliament when in session.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] The first broadcast from Parliament was of Question Time on 10 July 1946.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] The broadcasts were put onto the interstate network; however the Commission frequently commented on the disruption this caused to its programming in its annual reports.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] The ABC was also required to "secure its news for broadcasting purposes within the Commonwealth by its own staff, and abroad through such overseas news agencies and other overseas sources as it desired" (along with its own foreign correspondents).
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] The news department continued to expand, and was inaugurated on 1 June 1947.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] 9PA in Port Moresby was added to the ABC radio network on 1 July 1946.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] Additional stations were added to the network in Papua and New Guinea after this time, though they would later split from the ABC and form the National Broadcasting Corporation of Papua New Guinea in 1973, as part of preparations for the country's independence from Australia.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] In 1948, the ABC began operating experimental FM stations on 92.1 MHz in many capital cities.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] In 1975, the ABC introduced a 24-hour-a-day AM rock station in Sydney, 2JJ (Double Jay), which was eventually expanded into the national Triple J FM network.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] Also in 1975, *3ZZ Access Radio* began in Melbourne.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] It gave access to airtime to people from many language groups that had previously rarely been heard on air.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] It was closed in 1977, with its assets absorbed by 3EA (later to be part of SBS).
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] A classical music network was established in 1976 on the FM band, broadcasting from Adelaide.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] It was initially known as ABC-FM - referring both to its 'fine music' programming and type of radio modulation.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] In 1981, ABC Radio began carrying Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander broadcasts in Alice Springs and later North Queensland, while at the same time comedy and social history units were set up, and news and current affairs output expanded.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] The *Australian Broadcasting Corporation Act 1983* changed the name of the organisation from the Australian Broadcasting Commission to the Australian Broadcasting Corporation effective 1 July 1983.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] At the same time, television and radio operations were split into two separate divisions, with an overhaul of management, finance, property and engineering undertaken.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] Following this, ABC Radio was restructured significantly in 1985 - ABC Radio 1 became the ABC Metropolitan Radio network, while Radio 2 became known as Radio National (callsigns, however, were not standardised until 1990).
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] New programs such as *The World Today*, *Australia All Over* and the *Coodabeen Champions* were introduced, while ABC-FM established an Australian Music Unit in 1989.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] Radio Australia began to focus on the Asia-Pacific region, with coverage targeted at the south west and central Pacific, south-east Asia, and north Asia.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] Radio Australia also carried more news coverage, with special broadcasts during the 1987 Fijian coups d'état, Tiananmen Square massacre and the Gulf War.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] A Concert Music department was also established in 1985 to coordinate the corporation's six symphony orchestras, which in turn received a greater level of autonomy in order to better respond to local needs.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] Open-air free concerts and tours, educational activities, and joint ventures with other music groups were undertaken at the time to expand the Orchestras' audience reach.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] The Regional Radio stations provided local programming in *Breakfast* and *Drive*, but networked common content for most of their broadcasting hours.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] Some different, local market formats emerged, including the Darwin Metro 8DDD on FM105.7, and Gold Coast Regional, ABC Coast FM (4SCR), 91.7.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] A government initiative undertaken in 1987 known as the Second Regional Radio Network established nineteen new studios in regional areas (with an additional sixteen upgraded), as well as approximately 300 additional transmitters.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] At the same time, Radio National and ABC-FM were expanded into these areas.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] In August 1988, the Parliamentary Broadcast Network (PBN) was established under the National Metropolitan Radio Plan, as a dedicated station to carry the ABC's mandatory Parliamentary broadcasts on AM transmitters in each state capital as well as Newcastle and Canberra.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] Increasing pressure throughout the 1980s led the ABC to divest its orchestras in 1990.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] They formed Symphony Australia, an umbrella organisation that coordinates the now independent state-based orchestras (still owned by the ABC).
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] The Sydney Symphony Orchestra was the first to be corporatised in 1996 when Sydney Symphony Orchestra Holdings Pty Ltd was formed.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] During this period, the ABC set in motion plans to consolidate its properties and buildings in Sydney and Melbourne into single sites in each city.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] It was not until 1991, however that the corporation's Sydney radio and orchestral operations moved to a new building built by Leighton Contractors on a single site in the inner-city suburb of Ultimo.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] In Melbourne, the ABC Southbank Centre was completed in 1994, and now houses the radio division in Victoria as well as the Melbourne Symphony Orchestra.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] ABC-FM relaunched in 1994 as ABC Classic FM, accompanied by major changes to the station's music and programming.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] On 15 August 1994, the Parliamentary and News Network (PNN) was launched, to provide a continuous news network broadcast on the same frequencies used by the PBN, when Parliament was not sitting, and in 1996, it was named "ABC NewsRadio on the Parliamentary and News Network".
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] By the early 1990s, all major ABC broadcasting outlets moved to 24 hour-a-day operation, while regional radio coverage in Australia was extended with 80 new transmitters.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] Live television broadcasts of selected parliamentary sessions started in 1990.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] Trials for digital radio began in the 1990s, using the popular Eureka 147 standard.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] At the same time, the majority of operations were upgraded to fully digitised systems for program playout and storage, as well as a word processing system adapted specifically for the needs of the division's news services.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] In 1995, D-Cart digital technology developed by ABC Radio attracted worldwide interest and was sold to European, North American and Asian markets.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] The ABC used D-Radio, the first fully digital audio system, for Triple J.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] Up until the mid-1990s, the majority of the local radio stations identified on-air by frequency and callsign.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] This was changed in the 1990s, where *ABC Radio (region)* or *(region) FM* were used to distinguish the stations.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] In 2000, these two almost identical networks merged as ABC Local Radio.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] From this point all ABC Local Radio stations ceased to identify themselves according to their callsigns or other existing names, and instead use the format *(frequency) ABC (region)*, or *ABC (region)* where there are multiple frequencies broadcasting the same service.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] However, as the callsigns were used continuously for up to seventy years and are much shorter than the new names, many long-term listeners still use these callsigns to refer to ABC Local Radio stations.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] Throughout the 2000s, ABC Radio continued to upgrade its studio and transmitter facilities.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] The ABC attracted large audiences for its non-commercial radio coverage of the 2000 Summer Olympics, with a range of programming across its various networks.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] All networks celebrated 100 years of radio in 2001 with special broadcasts marking the event and a limited edition CD released, with highlights of the ABC's output since 1932.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] ABC NewsRadio began streaming its news programming online while its radio network broadcast parliament in 2002 - amongst the first of the corporation's radio networks to offer live, exclusive, streaming online.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] The service also expanded into the Gold Coast – the first new coverage area for the network in five years.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] In 2009 ABC Radio switched on DAB+ services, relaying its main channels and progressively launched new digital channels over subsequent years.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] Around 2010, ABC NewsRadio became the full name of what had been "ABC NewsRadio on the Parliamentary and News Network".
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] The ABC Radio app was launched in 2012, to be replaced by the ABC Listen app in September 2017, which included 45 ABC radio stations and audio networks.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] There was an organisational restructure of the ABC in 2017–18.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] In October 2015 a slight restructure of programming and news updates caused controversy.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] From 2016, *Morning* programs would be folded into longer *Breakfast* programs, followed by a new one-hour program, *Local Life*.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] There would also be a loss of four local radio news bulletins; instead, headlines would replace two afternoon full news bulletins.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] In January 2017, ABC Local Radio rebranded with a new logo, dropping the frequency number of each local radio station as part of the network's multiplatform philosophy.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] Also that year, 19 regional stations began to stream on the ABC Listen app.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] In April 2019, ABC Local Radio began a rollout of branding updates for its 44 regional bureaux, 10 regional stations dropping call signs from their names and two undergoing a significant name change to better identify their local region.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] In March 2026, ABC Local Radio reinstated callsign‑based branding across its on‑air presentation and visual identity for metropolitan stations.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] The metropolitan and regional stations originate most of their own programming and produce local news updates.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] There are local news websites for each station.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] When not airing local programming, the regional stations will usually simulcast their closest metropolitan station.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] The only exception is ABC Broken Hill, which will simulcast ABC Radio Adelaide because the town is on Central Time.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/abc-local-radio] Some programmes are aired first on Radio National, then on the ABC Local Radio network.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Some religious orders of various Christian Churches practice pescetarianism, including the Benedictines, Franciscans, Trappists, Carthusians and Cistercians.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Various Church leaders have recommended vegetarianism, including John Wesley (founder of the Methodist Church), William and Catherine Booth (founders of The Salvation Army), William Cowherd from the Bible Christian Church and Ellen G.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Cowherd, who founded the Bible Christian Church in 1809, helped to establish the world's first Vegetarian Society in 1847.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Organizations such as the Christian Vegetarian Association (CVA) work to promote the concept.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Additionally, many Christians may choose to practice vegetarianism or veganism as their Lenten sacrifice during the period of Lent.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Prior to the 6th century, Lent was normatively observed through keeping the Black Fast for forty days, with the allowance of one vegetarian meal with water after sunset.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Christian vegetarianism has not been a common dietary choice throughout Church history.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] One of the most important passages for Christian vegetarians is the creation narrative in the Book of Genesis.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] In this passage, God prescribes a plant-based diet not just for humans, but for all land-based non-human animals.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Christian vegetarians and vegans point out that it was this creation – where all creatures ate plants – that God then declared "very good" in verse 31.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Moreover, that God's initial creation was a vegan creation suggests that this is how God intended all his creatures to live.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Some Christian vegetarians have suggested that this eschatological view provides reasons to adopt a vegetarian or vegan diet here and now.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Moreover, the point has often been made that the *dominion* which humans are given over the non-human animals in Genesis 1:26–28 must be understood in light of Genesis 1:29–30 which decrees a plant-based diet for all creatures.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Genesis 1:26–28 has, it is acknowledged by Christian vegetarians, often been used to justify the eating of animals.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] In a survey of the scholarly literature on the relevant Hebrew terms, Carol J.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Adams lists *governing*, *ruling*, *shepherding*, *caring-for*, *nurturing*, and *leading about* as potential ways of understanding *dominion*, and notes that the common characteristic of these concepts "is their benignity".
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] The opening chapters of Genesis are, of course, only the beginning of the biblical story.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] And just as there are passages which can be cited in support of a Christian vegetarianism or veganism, so there are passages which suggest that eating animals is morally permissible.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] The most problematic passages for Christian vegetarians are those which include an explicit permission to eat animals.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Genesis 9:3–4 is the first such example.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] In this verse, God tells Noah and his family that animals will now be their food, although they are not to eat animal flesh which contains blood.[Genesis 9:3–4] However, the context of the passage remains contentious to the morality of eating Animals.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Similarly "The fear and dread of you shall rest on every animal of the earth, and on every bird of the air, on everything that creeps on the ground, and on all the fish of the sea; into your hand they are delivered" seems to emphasise the immorality and evil of the act.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] This new situation – that of humans eating animals – is then taken largely for granted in much of the biblical narrative.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Leviticus 11 records God giving the Israelites rules about what types of meat may be eaten, which implies that certain meats were acceptable.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Some Jewish and Christian vegetarians have attempted to minimize the importance of these passages.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] It has been suggested, for example, that God's permitting Noah and his family to eat meat was only ever intended as a temporary permission, and was given because all the plants had been destroyed as a result of the flood.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] These approaches are put under pressure, however, with the sheer number of passages which appear to presuppose the legitimacy of eating animals, and the normalcy with which meat eating is treated.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Another approach to these texts is to suggest that God reluctantly permitted the eating of animals due to human sinfulness.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] In other words, God permitted humans to eat non-human animals as a concession to the Fallen state of humanity.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Richard Young raises the possibility that both the introduction of animals into the human diet, and the use of animals in religious sacrifices, were concessions to a Fallen humanity that were used to deal with humanity where it was at.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] This approach allows the Christian vegetarian or vegan to take the entire biblical witness seriously, while also holding that God's preference is for a peace and shalom throughout creation.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Other passages of relevance to the practice of vegetarianism include Numbers 11, where the Israelites tired of manna, a food of which "The Rabbis of the Talmud held that [...] had whatever taste and flavor the eater desired at the time of eating" and which probably was not an animal product.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] A donkey temporarily given the ability to speak showed Balaam more than signs of sentience.[Numbers 22:21–33] Some people believe that the Book of Daniel also specifically promotes veganism as empowering.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Philo says that the Essenes, "being more scrupulous than any in the worship of God ... do not sacrifice animals ..., but hold it right to dedicate their own hearts as a worthy offering".
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] They maintained that the sacrifices "polluted" the Temple.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] The Christian Vegetarian Association of the UK claims that the word "meat" is not used in any one instance in the authorized version of either the Old or New Testament as relating only to animal food (e.g.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] The CVA states that when the first English translations of the Bible were created, the word for "meat" meant food in general.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] When any particular kind of food was designated, it was referred to as meal, flour or grain.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Christian vegetarians and vegans often appeal to the ethic that Jesus embodied, and called people to emulate, in making their case for a distinctively Christian vegetarianism.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] To begin with, Jesus inaugurated the Kingdom of God, but his Kingdom did not involve the exercise of power as humans tend to think of it.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Christian vegetarians also stress the importance Jesus laid on *peace* and *inclusion*.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] These and other aspects of Jesus's attitudes towards others are used to extract ethical principles which, according to Christian vegetarians and vegans, lead one to a vegetarian or vegan lifestyle.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Jesus's eating of fish[Luke 24] and telling his disciples where to catch fish, before cooking it for them to eat,[John 21] is a common subject in Christian ethical vegetarian and vegan writings.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] The original version does not mention fish at all and only bread.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] The Bible does not explicitly state that Jesus ate any meat, and Webb cites the fact that no lamb is mentioned at the Last Supper as evidence that he did not.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Andy Alexis-Baker has appealed to biblical scholarship to argue that biblical passages often need nuanced interpretation, and to guard against a wooden literalism.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] For example, he cites the work of Gerald O'Collins, SJ, who suggests that differences between the way Luke describes this appearance in Luke 24:41–43 and in Acts 1, and a tension between Luke 24:41–43 and 1 Corinthians 6, preclude us from reading this verse literally.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Vujicic explains this passage by appealing to a so-called *synoptic principle*.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] In the tenth chapter of the Acts of the Apostles, there is an account of a vision given to the Apostle Peter.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] In this vision, Peter is shown a large sheet being lowered from heaven by its four corners.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Christian vegetarians and vegans argue that this passage is not about which animals one may or may not eat but it is about who the Gospel is for.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] According to Laura Hobgood-Oster, "The vision, it seems, is not about eating animals; rather it is about extending hospitality to all humans.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Vujicic writes, "In the sheet were also so called CLEAN animals.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Peter could have at least selected some sheep or cattle and killed but he didn't." According to Vujicic, the reason Peter did not simply take up and eat a *clean* animal was because Peter was in fact a vegetarian.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Peter is reported as describing himself as a vegetarian in the apocryphal Pseudo-Clementine Homilies.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Most Christians maintain that Jesus's teaching in Mark 7[Mark 7:5–21] demonstrates that Christians can eat whatever they want, that dietary choices are a matter of "Christian liberty", and that therefore vegetarianism or veganism could never be obligatory for Christians.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Christian vegetarians and vegans counter that the point of Jesus's teaching in Mark 7 is that his followers should concern themselves with the status of their heart which "informs our relationship with God, with each other, and the world".
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Vegetarianism appears to have been a point of contention within some early Christian circles, notably in Rome.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Paul also said, "The Spirit clearly says that in later times some will abandon the faith and follow deceiving spirits and things taught by demons.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Such teachings come through hypocritical liars, whose consciences have been seared as with a hot iron.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] In the fourth century some Jewish Christian groups maintained that Jesus was himself a vegetarian.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Epiphanius quotes the Gospel of the Ebionites where Jesus has a confrontation with the high priest.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Other early Christian historical documents observe that many influential Christians during the formative centuries of Christianity were vegetarian, though certainly not all.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Although early Christian vegetarianism appears to have been downplayed in favor of more "modern" Christian culture, the practice of vegetarianism appears to have been very widespread in early Christianity, both in the leadership and among the laity.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Origen's work *Contra Celsum* quotes Celsus commenting vegetarian practices among Christians he had contact with.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Although not vegetarian himself and vehemently against the idea that Christians must be vegetarians, Augustine nevertheless wrote that those Christians who "abstain both from flesh and from wine" are "without number".
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Followers of the Gnostic sect known as Catharism practiced pescatarianism as early as the Middle Ages.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] The Bible Christian Church founded by Reverend William Cowherd in 1809 followed a vegetarian diet.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Cowherd was one of the philosophical forerunners of the Vegetarian Society.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Cowherd encouraged members to abstain from eating of meat as a form of temperance.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Cowherd emphasized that vegetarianism was good for health, whilst eating meat was unnatural and likely to cause aggression.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] The Seventh-day Adventists present a health message that recommends vegetarianism and expects abstinence from pork, shellfish and other foods proscribed as "unclean" in Leviticus.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] A number of the founders of the Seventh-day Adventist Church, including Joseph Bates and Ellen White, adopted a vegetarian diet during the nineteenth century, and Ellen White reportedly received visions regarding the health benefits of a vegetarian diet.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] More recently, members of the Seventh-day Adventist Church in California have been involved in research into longevity due to their healthy lifestyle, which includes maintaining a vegetarian diet.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] This research has been included within a *National Geographic* article.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Another denomination with common origin, the Seventh Day Adventist Reform Movement recommends vegetarianism as a part of fellowship, with many of its members being practicing vegans as well.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Unlike injunctions against tobacco and alcohol, compliance with this part of the Doctrine and Covenants has never been made mandatory by the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (LDS Church), the largest Latter Day Saint denomination.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Many LDS Church leaders have expressed their views on the subject of meat, but since Joseph F.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Smith became church president in 1901, emphasis on refraining from meat has largely been dropped.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] An official church publication states, "[m]odern methods of refrigeration now make it possible to preserve meat in any season".
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Some members of the Religious Society of Friends (also known as Quakers) practice vegetarianism or veganism as a reflection of the Peace Testimony, extending non-violence towards animals.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Historically, the early vegetarian movement had many Quaker promoters.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Some Ranter groups – non-conformist Christian groups that existed in seventeenth-century England – were vegetarian.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] In 1891, the Friends' Anti-Vivisection Association was founded, later becoming the Animal Welfare and Anti-Vivisection Society and subsequently Quaker Concern for Animals, reflecting a longstanding institutional engagement with animal welfare within the Society of Friends.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] In 1902, the Friends Vegetarian Society was established as a Quaker organisation.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] More recently, Quaker Vegan Witness (QVW), founded in 2019, has continued this tradition, organising vegan witness activities within British Quaker communities.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Roman Catholic monastic orders such as the Carthusians and Cistercians follow a pescatarian diet.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Carmelites and others following the Rule of St.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Albert also maintain a vegetarian diet, although the old and sick are permitted to eat meat according to this rule of life.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] The Order of Minims, an order of friars founded by St.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Francis of Paola in the 15th century, goes further: in addition to the standard three religious vows of chastity, poverty, and obedience, its members take a fourth vow of vita quadragesimalis ("a Lenten way of life"), committing to perpetual abstinence from all meat, eggs, and dairy products.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Christian anarchists, such as Leo Tolstoy, Ammon Hennacy, and Théodore Monod, extend the Christian principles of compassion and nonviolence through following a vegetarian diet.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] The Christian Vegetarian Association (CVA) is an international, non-denominational Christian vegetarian organization that promotes responsible stewardship of God's creation through plant-based eating.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] The CVA produced the 2006 film *Honoring God's Creation*.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Sarx is a UK-based organization which aims to "empower Christians to champion the cause of animals and live peacefully with all God's creatures".
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Sarx publishes interviews with Christian vegans and vegetarians on its website, and provides people to speak at Churches in the UK on topics such as Christianity and veganism, animal welfare and faith, creation and animals.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] CreatureKind is an organization which exists "to encourage Christians to recognize faith-based reasons for caring about the well-being of fellow animal creatures used for food, and to take practical action in response".
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] It was founded by David Clough, Professor of Theological Ethics at the University of Chester, and is directed by Clough and Sarah Withrow King, an American author and deputy directory of the Sider Center at Eastern University.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] CreatureKind produces a course for churches to do which facilitates church groups to think through how Christians should respond to and treat animals.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Creation Care Church is a virtual Christian church community, founded in 2021, that teaches a Bible-based approach to caring for the earth and all its inhabitants, including living a compassionate vegan lifestyle that shows mercy to all of God's creatures.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Catholic Concern for Animals (CCA) is a charity which calls Catholics "to cherish and care for all of [God's] creation".
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] CCA has for "many years" promoted a vegetarian/vegan diet as a way of caring for creation, in particular animals.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] The group Evangelicals for Social Action have suggested that a vegan diet is a way of demonstrating Christian love and compassion to farmed animals, and argue in particular that this is what a consistently pro-life ethic looks like.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Christian Vegetarians and Vegans UK is an organization seeking to promote a vegetarian/vegan lifestyle in the Church in the UK.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Quaker Vegan Witness (QVW) is a contemporary Quaker movement founded in 2019, focused on animal ethics and vegan living within Quaker communities.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Since its founding, QVW has organized witness activities and educational sessions at Quaker Yearly Meeting.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] During Lent some Christian communities, such as Orthodox Christians in the Middle East, undertake partial fasting eating only one light meal per day.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] For strict Greek Orthodox Christians and Copts, all meals during this 40-day period are prepared without animal products and are essentially vegan.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Unlike veganism, however, abstaining from animal products during Lent is intended to be only temporary and not a permanent way of life.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Catholic laity traditionally abstain from animal flesh on Fridays and through the Lenten season leading up to Easter (sometimes being required to do so by law, see fasting and abstinence in the Roman Catholic Church), some also, as a matter of private piety, observe Wednesday abstinence.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] *Fish* is not considered proper meat in any case (see pescetarianism, though the Eastern Orthodox allow fish only on days on which the fasting is lessened but meat still not allowed).
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] For these practices, "animal rights" are no motivation and positive environmental or individual health effects only a surplus benefit; the actual reason is to practice mortification and some marginal asceticism.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Oriental Orthodox, Eastern Orthodox, and Eastern Catholic monastics abstain from meat year-round, and many abstain from dairy and seafood as well.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Through obedience to the Orthodox Church and its ascetic practices, the Orthodox Christian seeks to rid himself or herself of the *passions*, or the disposition to sin.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] In Western Christianity, fasting is observed during the forty-day season of Lent by many communicants of the Catholic Church, Lutheran Churches, Anglican Communion, Methodist Churches and the Western Orthodox Churches to commemorate the fast observed by Christ during his temptation in the desert.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] While some Western Christians fast during the entire season of Lent, Ash Wednesday and Good Friday are emphasized by Western certain Christian denominations as especially important days of fasting within the Lenten season.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] According to Canon Law, Roman Catholics are required to abstain from meat (defined as all animal flesh and organs, excluding water animals) on Ash Wednesday and all Fridays of Lent including Good Friday.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Ash Wednesday and Good Friday are also fast days for Catholics ages 18 to 60, in which one main meal and two half-meals are eaten, with no snacking.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Canon Law also obliges Catholics to abstain from meat on the Fridays of the year outside of Lent (excluding certain holy days) unless, with the permission of the local conference of bishops, another penitential act is substituted.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Exceptions are allowed for health and necessity like manual labor and not causing offense when being a guest.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] The restrictions on eating meat on these days is solely as an act of penance and not because of a religious objection to eating meat.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] The United States Conference of Catholic Bishops has made substitution of a different penitential or charitable act an option for ordinary Fridays in their territory.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] After previous abolition, the Catholic Bishops' Conference of England and Wales restored the meatless ordinary Friday requirement for their territory effective September, 2011.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] A popular misconception is that Pope Gregory I (who ruled from 590 to 604, and who is also a canonized saint) declared that rabbits were not meat.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] This is apparently a corruption of a manuscript in which Saint Gregory of Tours described one person (who was also ill and might not have been Catholic) eating a rabbit fetus during Lent.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] The rules are widely ignored; a 2016 survey found that only 62% of U.S.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Catholics said they avoid meat on Fridays during Lent.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Refrain from eating meat (bloody foods) on all Fridays in Lent, substituting fish for example.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Eliminate a food or food group for the entire season.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Especially consider saving rich and fatty foods for Easter.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Consider not eating before receiving Communion in Lent.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Abstain from or limit a favorite activity (television, movies, etc.) for the entire season, and spend more time in prayer, Bible study, and reading devotional material.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] It is the practice of many Lutherans to abstain from alcohol and meat on the Fridays of Lent; a Black Fast has been historically kept by Lutherans on Good Friday.
[src:christian-vegetarianism/christian-vegetarianism] Methodism's historic liturgical book *The Sunday Service of the Methodists* (put together by John Wesley), as well as The Directions Given to Band Societies (25 December 1744), mandate fasting and abstinence from meat on all Fridays of the year (except Christmas Day, if it falls on a Friday).
